                                "question": "Why does a bank go bankrupt? Explain.",
                                "answer": "A bank goes bankrupt or becomes insolvent (দেউলিয়া) primarily when it suffers a severe liquidity crisis and its total liabilities exceed the fair market value of its total realizable assets, making it incapable of honoring its depositors' cash withdrawal demands.This financial failure typically occurs due to reckless credit policies that lead to a high volume of Non-Performing Loans (NPLs) or bad debts. When a bank lends out its depositors' money to non-viable projects and fails to recover the principal and interest, its capital base erodes. If panic spreads, a sudden \"bank run\" (where a massive number of depositors rush to withdraw their funds simultaneously) can completely deplete the bank's remaining cash reserves, forcing it into bankruptcy."
