                                "answer": "Para 1: Core Concept\n\nA garnishee order is a legal directive issued by a court of law ordering a bank to freeze or withhold funds from a judgment debtor’s bank account to satisfy an outstanding debt or decree owed to a judgment creditor.\n\n\nPara 2: Underlying Purpose and Process\n\nThe primary reason for issuing a garnishee order is to safeguard the legal rights of a creditor by preventing a defaulting debtor from clearing or hiding their money. When a court finds that a debtor is refusing or failing to pay their dues despite a formal verdict, it attaches the debtor's account balance. Upon receiving this order, the bank is legally compelled to stop honoring any cheques or withdrawal requests made by the account holder up to the specified amount, ensuring the money remains secured until it can be legally transferred to clear the creditor's claim."
