                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "\"Increasing own capital instead of increasing deposits\" will be more effective in solving the bank's problem—Evaluate the validity of this central bank directive in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Core Stance and Evaluation:\n\nThe directive issued by the central bank—ordering 'BC' Bank to \"increase its own capital instead of expanding its public deposits\"—is highly justified, appropriate, and acts as the most effective structural remedy to save the institution from insolvency.2. The Flaw of Increasing Deposits in a Crisis:\n\nThe stem notes that due to massive defaults in the housing sector, 'BC' Bank's \"actual liabilities exceeded its assets\" (সম্পদ থেকে প্রকৃত দায়ের পরিমাণ বেশি হয়ে যায়). Bank deposits are fundamentally legal liabilities because the bank is contractually bound to return that money to savers upon demand, alongside regular interest payments. If a fundamentally weak bank tries to mask its cash crunch by collecting more public deposits, it is simply accumulating even more high-cost liabilities. In a default-heavy climate, this would deepen its financial distress and increase the risk of a systemic bank run.3. Financial Cushioning through Own Capital:\n\nOn the other hand, increasing \"own capital\" (নিজস্ব মূলধন) through equity expansion, retaining earnings, or issuing new shares brings stable, non-repayable funds into the bank's balance sheet. This fresh capital acts as an unshakeable asset cushion that does not carry withdrawal pressure. According to central banking regulations (such as Basel frameworks), a strong capital-to-risk-weighted-assets ratio directly absorbs loan write-offs and provisioning shocks. It instantly corrects the asset-liability imbalance, shields depositors from losses, and restores public trust in the bank's long-term survival.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, when a bank's structural liabilities outweigh its real assets, adding more public deposits is a counterproductive strategy that worsens the deficit. The central bank's directive to inject core equity capital is the only mathematically sound solution to absorb bad debt shocks and restore financial solvency, rendering the policy completely valid and justified."
