                                                "answer": "Basel-II was formulated primarily to strengthen the financial stability, risk management capabilities, and operational transparency of international banking systems by introducing a more comprehensive, risk-sensitive framework for capital adequacy.Formulated by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS), it aimed to upgrade the previous Basel-I guidelines by structuring regulations around three core pillars: Minimum Capital Requirements (based on a refined assessment of credit, market, and operational risks), Supervisory Review Process, and Market Discipline (requiring robust public disclosures). It was designed to ensure that banks hold capital reserves that are directly proportional to the actual financial risks they undertake, thereby preventing sudden bank failures and protecting global economic interests."
