                                                "answer": "A bank is called a financial intermediary institution (আর্থিক মধ্যস্থ ব্যবসায়ী প্রতিষ্ঠান) because it acts as a commercial bridge connecting surplus economic units (savers) with deficit economic units (borrowers).The bank collects idle, scattered savings from individuals who have surplus cash by offering them a lower interest rate. It then pools these funds and distributes them as productive loans to entrepreneurs and businesses at a higher interest rate. The difference between the lending interest rate and the deposit interest rate (known as the spread) forms the bank's core operational profit. Since it systematically transfers capital from savers to investors, it functions as a financial intermediary."
