                                                "answer": "Para 1: Core Concept\n\nBasel-II is an international regulatory framework designed to ensure banking stability, and it is strictly applied across three core pillars: Minimum Capital Requirements, Supervisory Review Process, and Market Discipline.\n\n\nPara 2: Detailed Application Areas\n\nUnder the first pillar, Basel-II dynamically applies capital charges against three major banking risks: Credit Risk (risk of loan defaults), Market Risk (losses from price fluctuations in shares or bonds), and Operational Risk (losses from system failures, fraud, or internal errors). The second pillar applies to the regulatory oversight, granting central banks the power to evaluate how well commercial banks assess their own risk profiles. The third pillar applies to public disclosure, forcing banks to publish transparent financial health reports so market forces can reward strong institutions and penalize poorly managed ones."
