                                                "answer": "Para 1: Identification\n\nBased on its functions, 'Agra Bank' mentioned in the stem is a Specialized Bank (specifically an Agricultural Bank) that also performs regular commercial banking functions.\n\n\nPara 2: Theoretical Explanation\n\nA specialized bank is a financial institution established by the government or through a special legislative act to foster growth in a targeted socio-economic sector, such as agriculture, industry, or housing. While their primary objective is non-commercial—focusing instead on providing easy credit and technical aid to their target demographic—these institutions are frequently permitted to execute secondary commercial tasks, like mobilizing retail public savings and offering general utility services, to strengthen their fund base.\n\n\nPara 3: Contextual Application\n\nIn the stem, Agra Bank was deliberately formed by the government with the primary welfare goal of advancing agricultural development by providing farmers with low-interest credit and easy-term financing. However, to sustain its operations and integrate into the broader financial system, it also accepts savings from general citizens and provides loans. Since its organizational roots and core financial mandates are dedicated to a specific economic priority (agriculture), it functions fundamentally as a specialized bank."
