                                                "answer": "Para 1: Core Concept\n\nA bank is called a \"borrower of borrowed money\" because its primary business model relies on collecting funds by borrowing from depositors at a lower interest rate and then lending those exact funds to borrowers at a higher rate.\n\n\nPara 2: Detailed Mechanism\n\nA bank does not operate primarily on its own equity capital. Instead, it creates liabilities by accepting various forms of savings, current, and fixed deposits from the general public, which legally makes the bank a debtor or borrower to its depositors. The bank then turns around and acts as a creditor by investing or lending this accumulated capital to businesses and individuals. Since the raw material of a bank's lending operation consists entirely of funds it has previously borrowed from its account holders, it is accurately termed a borrower of borrowed money."
