                                                "answer": "Para 1: Identification\n\nBased on organizational structure, 'Kollol Bank' is a Branch Bank.\n\n\nPara 2: Theoretical Explanation\n\nBranch banking is a highly integrated banking system where a corporate financial institution carries out its massive nationwide or international business operations through a vast network of retail offices called branches. All these auxiliary units operate under the unified administrative control, operational guidelines, and legal identity of a single centralized head office. This structural framework allows the bank to efficiently mobilize national capital, diversify risks geographically, and extend corporate and retail credit across diverse financial markets.\n\n\nPara 3: Contextual Application\n\nThe stem highlights that Kollol Bank does not limit its presence to a single locality; rather, it actively collects deposits and issues credit across various districts and upazilas throughout the country. Furthermore, it has successfully expanded its commercial footprints beyond national borders to tap into global markets. Because its corporate infrastructure relies on multiplying operational desks globally under a single unified headquarters, it perfectly fits the structural profile of a branch bank."
