                                                "answer": "Para 1: Core Concept\n\nA branch bank is superior to a unit bank primarily because of its large-scale operational advantages, geographic risk diversification, and ability to easily transfer funds across different regions via a centralized head office.\n\n\nPara 2: Comparative Analysis\n\nUnlike a unit bank, which operates out of a single isolated office and is highly vulnerable to localized economic downturns, a branch banking system spreads its operations over various territories. This widespread presence allows it to collect idle savings from cash-surplus rural regions and safely channel them as credit into industrial urban centers. Furthermore, branch banks enjoy economics of scale, attract highly skilled management, offer widespread remittance facilities, and maintain superior financial stability, because a loss in one branch can easily be absorbed by profits earned in another."
