                                                "text": "Based on functions, what type of bank are Bank X and Bank Y described in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "Para 1: Identification\n\nBased on their functions, both Bank X and Bank Y described in the stem are Commercial Banks.\n\n\nPara 2: Theoretical Explanation\n\nA commercial bank is a profit-driven financial intermediary whose primary functional mandate revolves around mobilizing short-term idle savings from the public in the form of deposits and utilizing those accumulated funds to extend short-term loans or overdrafts to traders, businesses, and individuals. Their income is derived from the interest rate spread—the difference between the lower interest rate paid to depositors and the higher interest rate charged to borrowers—while simultaneously offering essential utility services like cheque clearing, bill payments, and money transfers.\n\n\nPara 3: Contextual Application\n\nThe stem explicitly mentions that Bank X and Bank Y are fundamentally engaged in the core business of \"collecting savings and granting loans.\" Even though they are structured physically as branch networks, their functional classification is entirely dictated by these financial activities. Because their primary economic purpose is to act as intermediaries dealing with public deposits and short-term credit distribution to generate profits, they perfectly embody the characteristics of commercial banks."
