                                                "answer": "Para 1: Core Concept\n\nA bill of exchange is an unconditional written order signed by one party (the drawer) directing another party (the drawee) to pay a fixed sum of money to a specified person (the payee) or the bearer, either on demand or at a fixed determinable future time.\n\n\nPara 2: Underlying Mechanism and Utility\n\nUnder the Negotiable Instruments Act, a bill of exchange serves as a crucial credit instrument in trade and commerce, particularly in domestic and international wholesale transactions. When a seller supplies goods to a buyer on credit, the seller draws a bill of exchange which the buyer formally signs as \"accepted.\" This legal instrument gives the seller security, and if the seller faces an urgent need for cash before the bill matures, they can take it to a commercial bank and get it discounted for immediate funds, thereby keeping business liquidity fluid."
