                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Explain the qualitative methods of credit control.",
                                                "answer": "Para 1: Core Concept\n\nThe qualitative (or selective) methods of credit control are regulatory tools used by a central bank to direct or restrict the flow of credit into specific sectors of the economy rather than altering the total money supply universally.\n\n\nPara 2: Key Methods Explained\n\nUnlike quantitative methods, qualitative methods are applied selectively to check speculative lending in unproductive sectors while boosting priority industries. Key qualitative techniques include rationing of credit (fixing loan ceilings for specific industries), changing margin requirements (altering the percentage of collateral value against which a loan can be issued), moral suasion (informal requests and letters from the central bank advising commercial banks to adopt certain credit guidelines), and direct action (imposing penalties or revoking the license of non-compliant banks). These actions ensure credit channels align with national economic priorities."
