                                                "text": "Describe the comparative differences between A Bank Ltd. and B Bank Ltd. mentioned in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "Para 1: Identification\n\nBased on their regulatory framework and legal status, A Bank Ltd. is a Scheduled Bank (or enlisted bank) under the direct supervision of the central bank, whereas B Bank Ltd. functions as an Autonomous Bank (or non-scheduled bank) governed by its own special charter.\n\n\nPara 2: Theoretical Core Differences\n\nThe primary structural differences between these two banking classifications lie in their regulatory obedience, capital compliance, and institutional dependency. A scheduled bank must strictly adhere to all statutory provisions, reserve requirements (SLR and CRR), and clearing house guidelines mandated by the central bank. In return, it gains financial backing. Conversely, an autonomous bank operates independently under its own unique legislative charter or administrative rules. While it enjoys extreme operational flexibility and makes self-determined credit policies, it lacks standard inter-bank clearing privileges and automatic emergency loan facilities from the central regulator.\n\n\nPara 3: Contextual Comparison\n\nIn the stem, A Bank Ltd. strictly complies with the guidelines of the \"guardian bank\" (the central bank), identifying it as a scheduled commercial bank. B Bank Ltd., however, runs entirely on its own self-made regulations, marking it as an autonomous entity. Financially, A Bank Ltd. is safer for general depositors because its liquidity is backed by mandatory central reserves, and it can easily clear cross-bank cheques through the central clearing house. B Bank Ltd., while highly efficient in executing localized or specialized mandates without external red tape, carries higher institutional liquidity risks as it cannot automatically claim clearing house desk rights or emergency capital injections from Bank C during a sudden financial crisis."
