                                "category": "Knowledge",
                                "question": "What is the dishonor of a cheque?",
                                "answer": "The dishonor of a cheque refers to a situation where a bank refuses to pay the amount specified on a cheque when it is presented by the holder for clearance or cash."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-012-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "Why is endorsement of a cheque required? Explain.",
                                "answer": "Endorsement of a cheque is required to legally transfer its ownership and the right to collect payment from one person to another. When an order cheque needs to be transferred to a third party, the designated payee must sign their name on the back of the instrument to legally authorize the bank to disburse the funds to the new holder.Without a proper endorsement, the financial negotiability of an order cheque comes to a halt, and the bank will decline processing it. This mechanism acts as an authentication layer that ensures transaction security, verifies a legitimate chain of title, and assigns legal accountability to the endorser if the instrument is later dishonored."
