                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-015-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "What is meant by a clearing house? Explain.",
                                "answer": "A clearing house (নিকাশঘর) is an institutional arrangement operated under the supervision of the central bank where representatives of scheduled commercial banks meet daily to settle their mutual interbank claims, checks, and financial balances smoothly and securely.Instead of physically carrying heavy amounts of cash between bank buildings to pay off mutual liabilities, banks present their claims electronically or physically at the clearing house. The net outstanding debit or credit balances are then adjusted through the respective commercial banks' current accounts maintained with the central bank, which maximizes transaction speed and reduces the risk of cash movement."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-016",
                                "category": "Knowledge",
                                "question": "What is a stale cheque?",
                                "answer": "A stale cheque is a cheque that is presented to the bank for payment after its statutory validity period (which is exactly 6 months or 180 days from the date of issue written on the instrument in Bangladesh) has expired."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-016-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "Why is an order cheque safer than a bearer cheque? Explain.",
                                "answer": "An order cheque is significantly safer than a bearer cheque because it contains a built-in layer of identity verification. An order cheque is explicitly payable to a specific individual or to their order, meaning the bank is legally obligated to verify the identity and signature of the presenter before releasing funds over the counter.Conversely, a bearer cheque can be cashed instantly by whoever physically holds and presents it, without any rigorous verification. If a bearer cheque is lost or stolen, an unauthorized person can easily claim the money, whereas if an order cheque is lost, a random finder cannot cash it without forging signatures and facing legal detection, ensuring much greater security."
