                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-020-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "Explain the significance of the phrase \"Not Negotiable\".",
                                "answer": "The phrase \"Not Negotiable\" (হস্তান্তরযোগ্য নহে) written on a crossed cheque or a negotiable instrument signifies that the instrument can still be physically transferred, but it strips away its legal feature of fluid negotiability. This means that the transferee (the person who receives the instrument) cannot get a better legal title or ownership right than what the transferor (the person who gave it) actually possessed.The primary significance of this clause is to maximize transactional security and eliminate third-party fraud. If an instrument marked \"Not Negotiable\" is lost or stolen and subsequently transferred to an innocent third party, that third party does not acquire a legal right to the money because the original thief had a defective title. Therefore, it completely shields the true owner and the drawer from financial losses arising from a chain of unauthorized transfers."
