                                "answer": "When a cheque is lost, immediate actionable steps must be taken by both the drawer and the holder to prevent fraudulent cash-outs or unauthorized misappropriation. The foremost duty of the holder is to instantly inform the drawer about the loss of the instrument.Subsequently, the drawer must issue a formal, written \"Stop Payment\" order to their respective bank branch, specifying the cheque number, date, and amount. Upon receiving this directive, the bank flags the account and freezes that specific instrument. Additionally, filing a General Diary (GD) at the local police station provides a solid legal shield against any future financial disputes or forgery claims arising from the lost cheque."
