                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "Why is the use of a cheque more universal than a bill of exchange? Explain.",
                                "answer": "The use of a cheque is more universal than a bill of exchange because a cheque offers much higher liquidity, administrative simplicity, and structural speed. A cheque is drawn on a specific bank and is always payable immediately on demand, making it readily acceptable in daily transactions. It does not require any formal acceptance process from the debtor before it becomes valid.Conversely, a bill of exchange is typically drawn on an individual or business entity rather than a bank, often involves a deferred maturity date, and strictly requires the formal written acceptance of the drawee to be legally enforceable. Because banks act as highly trusted, standardized financial intermediaries, cheques bypass the individual credit risks associated with bills of exchange, leading to their universal adoption in modern commerce."
