                                "answer": "The significance of the words \"Not Negotiable\" (হস্তান্তরযোগ্য নহে) written across a crossed cheque is that it strips the instrument of its fully negotiable character while leaving it transferable. It protects the true owner by ensuring that any subsequent holder cannot acquire a better title to the cheque than the person from whom they took it.Under Section 130 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, if a cheque marked \"Not Negotiable\" is stolen or fraudulently transferred, even an innocent third-party purchaser who takes it in good faith and for value will get a defective title. Therefore, if a fraudster cashes it, the true owner retains the legal right to recover the full amount from the recipient, making it an excellent safeguard against theft."
