                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "What is meant by an order cheque?",
                                                "answer": "An order cheque is a cheque that is made payable to a specific person or to their order. This means the bank will pay the amount only to the person whose name is mentioned on the cheque, or to anyone else to whom that person formally directs or endorses the payment.To cash or transfer an order cheque, the identity of the holder must be verified by the bank, and it requires the endorsement (signature on the back) of the payee if it is transferred to a third party. Consequently, it offers a higher degree of security than a bearer cheque, as it cannot be easily cashed by an unauthorized finder if lost."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "Why is the cheque mentioned in the stem secure? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The cheque mentioned in the stem is secure because it is a \"Restrictive Crossed Cheque\" (Account Payee Cheque), which prohibits cash payment over the bank counter and ensures the money goes directly into the specified payee's account.According to the stem, Mr. Suman drew a crossed cheque containing the words \"A/C Payee\" between two parallel lines. When a cheque is crossed in this manner, it loses its negotiability by mere delivery, and the paying bank is legally restricted from making a cash disbursement over the counter. Instead, the money must be deposited into the bank account of the designated payee (Ashik) through a clearing house.This mechanism drastically minimizes the risk of fraud, theft, or misappropriation. Even if the cheque is lost or stolen, an unauthorized person cannot cash it over the counter, and any attempt to deposit it into another account leaves a clear, traceable digital trail. Therefore, Ashik's friend was entirely correct in calling it a highly secure cheque."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Is the medium of financial transaction used by Mr. Suman with his employees in the stem correct? Analyze.",
                                                "answer": "1. Compliance with Modern Corporate Practices:\n\nYes, the medium of financial transaction used by Mr. Suman with his employees—paying salaries via crossed \"A/C Payee\" cheques—is completely correct, highly appropriate, and aligns with modern business standards. In contemporary corporate environments, managing large-scale payroll through cash involves high operational risks, whereas banking channels ensure safety, legality, and systemic order.2. Ensuring Financial Security and Risk Mitigation:\n\nBy utilizing crossed cheques with an \"A/C Payee\" instruction, Mr. Suman effectively eliminates the risks of handling massive amounts of physical cash, such as theft, robbery, or internal embezzlement. Since the funds can only move from the employer’s corporate account directly into the specific employee’s bank account, it safeguards both the organization's capital and the employees' hard-earned remuneration.3. Maintenance of Transparent Documentation and Audit Trails:\n\nTransacting through crossed cheques automatically creates an indisputable, permanent digital and physical audit trail in the banking system. This transparency is crucial for Mr. Suman’s business to maintain accurate accounting records, facilitate seamless financial audits, and easily present valid proof of salary disbursement to tax authorities or labor regulatory bodies when required.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, Mr. Suman's decision to use crossed cheques for salary disbursement is exemplary. It protects the new employee Ashik and others from losing their money, reduces administrative hassle, and fosters institutional transparency, making it the most logical and correct financial medium for employee transactions."
