                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "What is meant by a crossed cheque?",
                                                "answer": "A crossed cheque is a cheque that has two parallel transverse lines drawn across its face, usually on the top left corner, with or without words like \"And Co.\", \"Not Negotiable\", or \"Account Payee\". This crossing serves as an instruction to the paying banker that the cheque cannot be cashed directly over the counter.The primary purpose of crossing a cheque is to enhance security by ensuring that the payment is routed strictly through a banking channel into a bank account. This provides a clear audit trail and drastically reduces the risk of fraud, theft, or unauthorized encashment, making it much safer than an open or bearer cheque."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What is the reason behind the bank's refusal to pay the amount of the cheque mentioned in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The reason behind the bank's refusal to pay the amount of the cheque mentioned in the stem is that the cheque became a \"Stale Cheque\" (বাসি চেক) due to the expiration of its statutory validity period.According to banking laws and standard practices in Bangladesh, a cheque remains valid for exactly 6 months (180 days) from the date of its issue written on the instrument. If a cheque is presented to the bank after this 6-month window has closed, the bank is legally obligated to dishonor it and refuse payment, classifying it as stale.In the given stem, Salam Talukdar issued the cheque on February 10, 2024. The 6-month validity period of this cheque expired on August 10, 2024. However, Mr. Kalam deposited the cheque into his bank account on August 20, 2024, which was 10 days after its expiration date. Because the cheque had already become stale, the bank rightfully and legally refused to clear or honor the transaction."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Is it possible for Mr. Kalam, as mentioned in the stem, to realize his due money? Give arguments in support of your answer.",
                                                "answer": "1. Realization via Revalidation of the Cheque:\n\nYes, it is entirely possible for Mr. Kalam to realize his due money of BDT 500,000 despite the bank's refusal. The most straightforward and peaceful method is to approach the drawer, Mr. Salam Talukdar, and request him to revalidate the stale cheque by altering the date with his full signature or to issue a brand new cheque in place of the old one.2. Legal Rights Under the Negotiable Instruments Act:\n\nThe expiration of a cheque's validity period does not extinguish the underlying debt or liability between the two parties. Since Mr. Salam Talukdar remains legally indebted to Mr. Kalam for business transactions, Mr. Kalam still holds the legal right to claim his money under the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881.3. Recourse Through Legal Notice and Civil Suit:\n\nIf Mr. Salam Talukdar acts in bad faith and refuses to cooperate or issue a new cheque, Mr. Kalam can send him a formal legal notice demanding the settlement of the dues. If that fails, Mr. Kalam can file a civil lawsuit in court for the recovery of the money based on his underlying business contracts and invoices, using the dishonored stale cheque as supporting evidence of the unpaid debt.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, while the physical stale cheque can no longer be directly processed by the bank, Mr. Kalam's legal right to receive his money remains intact. By either mutually renewing the cheque with Mr. Salam or pursuing standard legal channels for debt recovery, Mr. Kalam can successfully realize his due amount."
