                                                "answer": "1. Insufficiency of Funds in the Account:\n\nOne of the most frequent reasons for a cheque being dishonored is an insufficient balance in the drawer's account. If the amount specified on the cheque exceeds the actual clear funds available in the customer's account at the moment of presentation, the bank will refuse to honor the instrument and mark it as \"Refer to Drawer\" or \"Innsufficient Funds.\"2. Signature Mismatch or Lack of Endorsement:\n\nThe bank acts as a custodian of the customer's money and is legally required to verify authenticity before releasing funds. If the signature of the drawer on the cheque does not perfectly match the specimen signature preserved in the bank's database, or if the necessary endorsement on an order cheque is missing or irregular, the bank will immediately reject the payment.3. Expiration of Validity (Stale or Post-Dated Cheques):\n\nA cheque must be presented within its legal lifecycle, which is exactly 6 months from the written date in Bangladesh. If a cheque is presented after 6 months, it becomes a \"Stale Cheque\" (বাসি চেক) and is dishonored. Conversely, if it is presented before the date written on its face, it is considered a \"Post-Dated Cheque\" and the bank will decline processing it until that date arrives.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, while the discrepancy between words and figures was the specific trigger for Mr. Rayhan's cheque being dishonored, the banking system maintains rigid security protocols. Alterations without full counter-signatures, frozen accounts, insolvency of the drawer, or damaged/torn instruments are all critical factors that legally compel a bank to dishonor a cheque to protect financial integrity."
