                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "Which type of cheque does Mr. Ramzan use in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "Mr. Ramzan uses a \"Bearer Cheque\" (বাহক চেক) to provide monthly expenses to his son Mizan as described in the stem.A bearer cheque is a type of open cheque that can be cashed immediately over the bank counter by whoever holds the physical instrument and presents it to the paying teller. It does not require the holder to maintain a bank account or undergo rigorous identity verification, as the bank is authorized to pay the amount to the \"bearer\" of the document.In the given stem, Mizan takes the monthly BDT 7,000 cheque from his father, goes to the bank, and successfully withdraws the cash directly to meet his expenses without needing a personal bank account or facing any counter restrictions. This ease of instant cash disbursement confirms that Mr. Ramzan was using a standard bearer cheque for his son's convenience."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Between Mizan's scholarship cheque and the cheque given by his father, which one is better? Analyze.",
                                                "answer": "1. Comparative Security and Risk Mitigation:\n\nBetween the two instruments, Mizan's scholarship cheque—which is a Crossed Cheque—is undoubtedly better and safer than the bearer cheque given by his father. A bearer cheque carries extreme financial risk; if Mizan loses it on his way to the bank, any random finder can legally cash it over the counter, leaving no electronic or paper trail to catch the unauthorized person.2. Institutional Protection via Banking Channels:\n\nThe scholarship cheque issued by the Education Board requires Mizan to open a formal bank account because it is a crossed cheque. This structural mechanism ensures that the BDT 5,000 cannot be stolen or misappropriated, as the funds are strictly transferred from the Board's treasury account into Mizan's specific personal account through an institutional clearing house.3. Financial Inclusion and Accountability:\n\nFurthermore, the crossed scholarship cheque encourages financial discipline by introducing a student to formal banking systems, creating an immutable digital audit trail. While his father's bearer cheque offers immediate liquidity, it lacks the institutional security, tracking capability, and professional safety standards inherent in a crossed organization-issued cheque.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the crossed scholarship cheque is superior due to its advanced safety features. It completely eliminates the threat of financial fraud or loss, ensures that the money reaches the rightful beneficiary, and creates a transparent, recorded financial footprint, making it far better than a risky bearer cheque."
                                        }
                                ]
                        },
