                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Why is endorsement of a cheque required? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "Endorsement (অনুমোদন) of a cheque is required to legally transfer its ownership and right to receive payment from one person to another. When an order cheque needs to be transferred to a third party, the payee must sign their name on the back of the instrument to authorize the bank to pay the new holder.Without a proper endorsement, the financial negotiability of an order cheque is legally halted, and the bank will refuse to process the payment. It acts as an authentication mechanism, ensuring safety, proving the legitimate chain of title, and fixing the legal responsibility of previous holders in case the cheque is later dishonored."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of cheque is described in the stem? Present it with a diagram.",
                                                "answer": "The financial instrument described in the stem is a \"General Crossed Cheque\" (সাধারণ দাগকাটা চেক).According to the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, when two parallel transverse lines are drawn across the face of a cheque (usually at the top left corner) without any restrictive words like \"Account Payee\" or \"Not Negotiable\", it is classified as a general crossing. The primary legal effect of this structure is that the bank is strictly prohibited from making a cash payment directly over the counter; instead, the money must be routed into a bank account.In the given stem, Mr. Rayhan drew two parallel lines on the left side of the cheque before handing it over to Mr. Ripon, which perfectly aligns with the legal format of a general crossed cheque. Below is a visual representation showing how a general crossing is executed on an instrument:"
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Does the rejection of the cheque mentioned in the stem seem logical to you? Analyze your opinion.",
                                                "answer": "1. Evaluation of Statutory Validity Timeline:\n\nYes, the bank's decision to reject the cheque presented by Mr. Ripon is completely logical, lawful, and justified. Under standard banking laws and the Negotiable Instruments Act in force in Bangladesh, a cheque possesses a strict statutory validity lifespan of exactly 6 months (180 days) from the date written on its face.2. Calculation of the Expiration Window:\n\nIn this case, Mr. Rayhan issued and dated the cheque on January 4, 2023 (04-01-2023). Therefore, the 6-month legal window during which the bank was authorized to honor and clear this financial instrument expired on July 4, 2023. Any attempt to clear the funds after this date automatically changes the legal status of the document.3. Transition to a Stale Instrument:\n\nBecause Mr. Ripon went abroad for medical treatment and delayed his presentation until July 10, 2023 (10-07-2023), he presented it exactly 6 days after the legal expiration date. At this point, the cheque had legally transformed into a \"Stale Cheque\" (বাসি চেক). Bankers are legally mandated to reject stale instruments to prevent obsolete transactions and protect the drawer's account security.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the rejection was not due to the general crossing or a lack of funds, but entirely due to the passage of time. The bank acted in strict compliance with monetary regulations. To recover his dues, Mr. Ripon must now logically approach Mr. Rayhan to revalidate the old date with a fresh signature or issue a completely new crossed cheque."
