                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is a promissory note?",
                                                "answer": "A promissory note is a written, unconditional promise signed by one person to pay a specific sum of money to another specified person or to their order at a fixed or determinable future time."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "\"A bearer cheque does not require endorsement\" — Explain.",
                                                "answer": "\"A bearer cheque does not require endorsement\" because, by legal definition under banking law, its ownership is transferred from one person to another by mere physical delivery. The words \"or bearer\" written on the face of the cheque authorize the bank to pay the specified sum of money to whoever holds and presents the instrument at the cash counter.Since the bank is not legally required to verify the identity of the person presenting a bearer cheque, there is no necessity for the payee to sign or write their name on the back of the instrument (endorsement) to transfer it. Consequently, it acts like liquid currency, offering maximum speed and convenience for transactions but carrying a significantly higher risk of theft or unauthorized cash-outs."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of cheque is the first cheque mentioned in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The first cheque (Figure 1) in image_d70959.png is a \"Restrictive Crossed Cheque\", specifically known as an \"Account Payee Cheque\" (প্রাপকের হিসাব সমান্তরাল দাগকাটা চেক).According to the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, when a cheque contains two parallel transverse lines drawn across its face with the specific words \"Account Payee\" or \"Payee's Account\" written within them, it constitutes a restrictive crossing. The legal effect of this crossing is that it strips the cheque of its fluid negotiability by mere delivery and acts as a strict directive to the paying bank that the funds cannot be paid in cash over the counter.In Figure 1, the drawer Manik has crossed the top-left corner of the cheque and written \"প্রাপকের হিসাব\" (Account Payee) between the lines. Even though the printed text says \"or bearer\" (অথবা বাহককে), the presence of the restrictive crossing overrides it completely. This means the bank must transfer the BDT 50,000 exclusively into the formal bank account of the designated payee, Mr. Karim, through the banking clearance network, making it an exceptionally secure instrument."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Comparative analyze the characteristics of both cheques mentioned in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Analysis of Crossing Styles and Restrictions:\n\nThe primary distinction between both cheques in image_d70959.png lies in their crossing styles. The first cheque (Figure 1) features a Restrictive Crossing (\"প্রাপকের হিসাব\" / Account Payee), meaning the funds can only be deposited directly into the bank account of the named payee, Mr. Karim. On the other hand, the second cheque (Figure 2) features a Special Crossing (\"ANZ ব্যাংক লি.\" / ANZ Bank Ltd.), which legally restricts the payment from being cleared through any bank other than ANZ Bank, acting as a direct institutional mandate.2. Comparative Security and Fraud Prevention Levels:\n\nBoth instruments provide enhanced security compared to open cheques, but they fulfill different protective functions. Figure 1 prioritizes individual safety by ensuring that only Mr. Karim can receive the BDT 50,000, creating an immutable electronic link to his identity. Figure 2 prioritizes channel safety, directing Sotota Bank PLC that it must route the BDT 1,20,000 exclusively through ANZ Bank Ltd.'s clearing account, reducing inter-organizational collection risks.3. Operational Clearance Mechanisms:\n\nFrom an operational standpoint, the clearance pathways for the two instruments differ significantly. To cash the first cheque, Mr. Karim must deposit it into his personal bank account at any commercial bank, which will then collect it from Ekota Bank. To clear the second cheque, the holder must route it specifically through an account maintained at ANZ Bank Ltd., as Sotota Bank will outright refuse to pay any other bank attempting to clear that instrument.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, while both cheques are structurally crossed to eliminate over-the-counter cash fraud, Figure 1 functions as an Account Payee restrictive instrument protecting the specific recipient's title, whereas Figure 2 functions as a Special Crossed instrument safeguarding the designated collection agency. Both types demonstrate how adjustments to crossing text can alter the security and routing mandates under the Negotiable Instruments Act."
                                        }
                                ]
