                                "meta": "Sylhet · 2025",
                                "type": "board",
                                "questions": [
                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is a crossed cheque?",
                                                "answer": "A crossed cheque is a cheque that bears two parallel transverse lines drawn across its face, indicating that it cannot be cashed directly over the counter and must be deposited into a bank account."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Who is the drawer of a cheque? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The drawer (আদেষ্টা) of a cheque is the person or account holder who writes, signs, and issues the cheque, directing their bank to pay a specific amount of money to a designated person or to the bearer.The drawer is the primary party to a cheque and must maintain a valid account with the bank upon which the cheque is drawn. By signing the cheque, the drawer authorizes the bank to deduct funds from their account, and they remain legally responsible to the holder if the bank refuses payment due to insufficient funds or other valid reasons."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of cheque did Mr. Ali receive?",
                                                "answer": "The cheque received by Mr. Ali in the stem is a \"Bearer Cheque\" (বাহক চেক).A bearer cheque is a type of open cheque that is payable to anyone who legally or physically holds the instrument and presents it to the bank's cash counter. The bank is not under any statutory obligation to verify the identity or authenticity of the person presenting such a cheque, and cash is disbursed immediately upon demand.In the given stem, Mr. Ali handed over the cheque to his house guard to withdraw the money. The guard was able to walk into the bank, present the instrument, and successfully withdraw the BDT 50,000 before running away. This ease of instant over-the-counter cash disbursement without identity verification confirms that the cheque received by Mr. Ali was a bearer cheque."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "How could Mr. Ali have ensured the security of the money he received? Analyze.",
                                                "answer": "1. Ensuring Security Through Cheque Crossing:\n\nMr. Ali could have easily ensured the safety of his BDT 50,000 by converting the open bearer cheque into a crossed cheque. By drawing two parallel transverse lines across the top-left corner of the cheque and writing \"Account Payee\" or \"And Co.\", he would have legally prohibited the bank from making a direct cash disbursement to the house guard or anyone else over the counter.2. Eliminating Handover Risks via Banking Channels:\n\nIf the cheque had been crossed, the money could only be routed through a formal banking channel into a designated bank account. The house guard would have been completely unable to cash it over the counter and run away with liquid money, effectively neutralizing the risk of theft or internal embezzlement by unverified individuals.3. Personal Cashment or Electronic Transfer Alternative:\n\nInstead of trusting a house guard with a highly fluid and risky instrument like an open bearer cheque, Mr. Ali should have personally visited the bank branch to cash it. Alternatively, he could have requested his debtor to transfer the funds electronically via modern internet banking or a digital wallet platform, which would have automatically created an indisputable, secure financial trail.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, Mr. Ali's financial loss was the direct result of gross negligence and a lack of awareness regarding standard banking practices. By utilizing a restrictive crossing on the cheque or handling the banking transaction personally, he could have fully secured his hard-earned money and prevented the house guard from taking advantage of the situation."
                                        }
                                ]
