                                                "answer": "The special room of Bangladesh Bank mentioned in the stem is the \"Clearing House\" (নিকাশঘর).As the guardian of the money market, the central bank operates the clearing house to streamline interbank check settlements and mutual financial obligations. According to banking law, all listed or scheduled commercial banks must maintain a portion of their deposits with the central bank, which enables the central bank to clear interbank transfers securely by adjusting their ledger balances in this dedicated institutional space.The stem explicitly mentions a \"special room\" where listed banks meet to clear and settle their mutual debts and claims arising from day-to-day transactions. This functional description perfectly corresponds to the operational definition of a clearing house, which acts as a foundational clearing pillar for the national payment architecture."
