                                                "answer": "1. Core Mechanism of Bank Rate Policy:\n\nThe first method adopted by Bangladesh Bank in the stem is the quantitative expansion of the Bank Rate Policy (ব্যাংক হার নীতি), where it raised the benchmark interest rate from 5.5% to 6%. By increasing the bank rate, the central bank makes borrowing more expensive for scheduled commercial banks, which forces them to raise their loan interest rates for public consumers, ultimately shrinking investment demands and reducing the velocity of physical money in the market.2. Core Mechanism of Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR):\n\nThe second method adopted is increasing the Cash Reserve Ratio or CRR (নগদ জমা অনুপাত নীতি). CRR is the mandatory statutory percentage of total customer deposits that scheduled commercial banks must deposit as physical cash reserves with Bangladesh Bank. By increasing the CRR threshold, the central bank directly freezes a massive volume of loanable funds inside the state vault, instantly draining excess liquidity out of the commercial banking system.3. Operational Speed and Direct Impact Comparison:\n\nWhile both are quantitative credit control tools, they differ significantly in execution speed and market impact. The Bank Rate Policy is an indirect mechanism that depends on commercial bank compliance and public consumer behavior over a longer time horizon to curb investment. Conversely, raising the CRR is a direct, aggressive mandate that immediately strips banks of liquid cash, producing an instant contractions in credit multiplication and spending capability.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, Bangladesh Bank strategically combined two vital monetary tools to tackle stubborn inflation. The initial shift in the Bank Rate was an attempt to regulate credit through cost mechanisms, while the subsequent decision to increase the CRR reflects a decisive, direct quantitative measure aimed at freezing structural market liquidity, making CRR a more forceful tool for immediate inflation stabilization."
