                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "\"A bearer cheque is less secure.\" - Explain.",
                                                "answer": "A bearer cheque is considered less secure because its ownership is transferred by mere physical delivery, and the bank is authorized to pay the amount to anyone who presents it at the counter. The paying bank is under no statutory obligation to verify the identity, name, or legitimacy of the person presenting a bearer cheque.Consequently, if a bearer cheque is lost or stolen, an unauthorized person or finder can easily walk into the bank, cash the instrument over the counter, and disappear. This complete lack of identity verification and absence of a traceable banking trail makes bearer cheques highly vulnerable to theft, fraud, and misappropriation."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "Explain the reason behind the bank's inability to pay the amount of the cheque mentioned in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "The reason behind the bank's inability to pay the amount of the cheque presented by Mr. Karim is that it has legally transformed into a \"Stale Cheque\" (বাসি চেক).Under standard banking regulations and commercial laws in Bangladesh, a cheque holds a strict statutory validity lifespan of exactly 6 months (180 days) from the date written on its face by the drawer. If a cheque is presented to the bank after this six-month threshold has crossed, the bank is legally obligated to reject it to protect the account holder's security and prevent obsolete debits.According to the stem, Mr. Nabi issued and dated the cheque on January 1, 2022 (01-01-2022). Therefore, the legal window during which the bank was authorized to clear and honor this instrument closed on July 1, 2022. Since Mr. Karim delayed presenting the cheque until August 1, 2022 (01-08-2022)—which is seven months after its issuance—the instrument had already expired, justifying the bank's direct refusal to disburse the funds."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Is it possible for Mr. Karim to collect his dues? Give your opinion regarding this.",
                                                "answer": "1. Confirmation of Legal Recovery Options:\n\nYes, it is entirely possible for Mr. Karim to collect his dues from Mr. Nabi. Although the specific paper instrument has expired and the bank has rightfully refused to cash it, the underlying commercial debt and Mr. Nabi's financial liability for the transaction remain fully valid under corporate law.2. Revalidation via Counter-Signature:\n\nThe most efficient mechanism for Mr. Karim to recover his money is to approach the original drawer, Mr. Nabi, and present the stale cheque to him. Mr. Nabi can legally revalidate the existing document by crossing out the old expired date, writing a fresh current date above it, and placing his full official signature right next to the alteration to authorize the change.3. Issuance of a Fresh Financial Instrument:\n\nAlternatively, if revalidating the old leaf is not preferred, Mr. Karim can request Mr. Nabi to officially cancel the stale cheque and issue a brand-new crossed or order cheque for the same amount. If Mr. Nabi acts in good faith, this completely resolves the liquidity issue, allowing Mr. Karim to deposit the new instrument and collect his funds smoothly through standard clearing channels.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, while the current physical cheque is legally dead at the bank counter, Mr. Karim's legal right to his money is not lost. By communicating with Mr. Nabi to either update the date on the old leaf or obtain a completely fresh cheque, Mr. Karim can easily overcome his administrative oversight and successfully recover his business dues."
