                                                "text": "In light of the stem, what type of cheque is this? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "In light of the stem, the cheque collected by Mr. Siddique's manager is a \"General Crossed Cheque\" (সাধারণ দাগকাটা চেক).According to Section 123 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, when a cheque features two parallel transverse lines drawn across its face—typically at the top-left corner—it is recognized as a general crossing. The primary legal implication of this marking is that the paying bank is strictly prohibited from paying physical cash directly over the counter. Instead, the money must be routed through an institutional banking channel and credited to a bank account.In the given stem, it is explicitly mentioned that Mr. Siddique felt relieved after seeing two parallel lines drawn on the left corner of the BDT 4,000,000 cheque. Since no specific restrictive text (like \"Account Payee Only\") or specific bank names were inscribed within those lines, it perfectly complies with the statutory definition and format of a general crossed cheque."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Does this cheque have any significance? Analyze in light of the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Elimination of Counter Cashment Risks:\n\nYes, this crossed cheque holds immense commercial significance, especially in the context of high-value business transactions. Since the cheque is worth a substantial BDT 4,000,000, sending a manager to fetch it as an open bearer cheque would pose an extreme security threat. The presence of the crossing lines ensures that no unauthorized finder or even a dishonest employee can cash the instrument directly over the bank counter.2. Compulsory Account Routing and Safety:\n\nThe primary significance of this cheque lies in its capacity to control liquidity risks. Because of the two parallel lines, the paying bank is legally obligated to refuse counter cashments and force the transaction through the interbank clearing house system. The entire BDT 4,000,000 must be deposited into a formal bank account, transforming a risky paper handling process into a highly secure, non-cash settlement.3. Manufacturing an Indisputable Audit Trail:\n\nFurthermore, a general crossed cheque acts as robust documentary evidence by creating a permanent digital audit trail within the financial system. Every step of the transaction—from the debtor's account debit to Mr. Siddique's account credit—is permanently recorded. This institutional transparency provides legal protection against embezzlement, fraud, and payment disputes between business parties.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the structural features of this crossed cheque provide the exact security mechanisms that justified Mr. Siddique's relief. By automatically blocking immediate physical cash outs and enforcing a completely traceable account-to-account transfer, the instrument eliminates operational vulnerabilities, rendering it an indispensable tool for safe, high-volume commercial commerce."
