                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of negotiable instrument is Mr. Johir's letter in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The letter issued by Mr. Johir to Mr. Dobir in the stem is a \"Bill of Exchange\" (বিনিময় বিল).According to Section 5 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, a bill of exchange is an unconditional written order signed by the maker (creditor) directing a certain person (debtor) to pay a specific sum of money only to, or to the order of, a certain person or to the bearer of the instrument at a fixed or determinable future time. A crucial operational requirement of a bill of exchange is that it must be presented to the debtor for formal \"Acceptance\" (স্বীকৃতি) before it becomes legally binding.In the given stem, Mr. Johir (the creditor) issued a written letter ordering Mr. Dobir (the debtor) to pay BDT 100,000 within 90 days. Furthermore, Mr. Dobir received the letter, wrote 'স্বীকৃতি' (Accepted) on it, and returned it to Mr. Johir. This three-party structure involving an unconditional order by a creditor followed by a formal written acceptance by a debtor perfectly satisfies the statutory definitions and characteristics of a bill of exchange."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Evaluate comparatively the letters of Mr. Johir and Mr. Dobir on the basis of negotiable instruments in light of the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Core Distinction in Instrument Classification:\n\nThe two letters described in the stem represent two entirely distinct categories of commercial credit instruments. While Mr. Johir's letter is a Bill of Exchange (বিনিময় বিল), Mr. Dobir's letter to Mr. Seazer is a Promissory Note (ওয়াদাপত্র বা প্রতিশ্রুতিপত্র). Both are recognized negotiable instruments under the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, but they operate through contrasting legal mechanisms.2. Comparative Analysis of Parties and Direction:\n\nThe primary structural difference lies in the number of initial parties and the nature of the mandate. Mr. Johir's bill of exchange originates as an order to pay issued by a creditor, involving three parties: the drawer (Mr. Johir), the drawee (Mr. Dobir), and the payee (Mr. Johir or an order party). Conversely, Mr. Dobir's promissory note is a voluntary promise to pay generated directly by the debtor himself. It involves only two primary parties: the maker/debtor (Mr. Dobir) and the payee/creditor (Mr. Seazer).3. Necessity of Formal Acceptance:\n\nAnother vital comparative element is the requirement for legal acceptance. Mr. Johir's letter had no operational validity until Mr. Dobir explicitly wrote \"Accepted\" on it, as bills of exchange require the drawee's formal consent to establish financial liability. In contrast, Mr. Dobir's letter to Mr. Seazer requires no such acceptance. Because Mr. Dobir himself initiated the document by explicitly vowing (ওয়াদা করে) to pay BDT 200,000 within two months, his signature as the maker immediately establishes primary legal liability.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, both letters serve as indispensable credit tools that facilitate trade by shifting cash obligations into the future. However, while Mr. Johir's instrument functions as a creditor's directive that requires a defensive written acceptance from the debtor, Mr. Dobir's letter functions as a debtor's proactive, self-binding acknowledgment of a debt. This structural contrast distinguishes the tri-party bill of exchange from the two-party promissory note in corporate transactions."
                                        }
                                ]
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-038",
                                "stem": "Mr. Rayhan gave a cheque of BDT 500,000 to his creditor Mr. Sijan on 05-01-2024. Mr. Sijan went abroad for medical treatment. Therefore, when Mr. Sijan went to deposit the cheque into his bank account on 01-08-2024 to withdraw the money, the bank expressed its inability to pay.",
                                "stemImage": "",
                                "meta": "College · 2025",
                                "type": "college",
                                "questions": [
                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is a bank draft?",
                                                "answer": "A bank draft is a secure financial instrument issued by one branch of a bank directing another branch of the same bank (or a correspondent bank) to pay a specified sum of money to a designated payee on demand."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "What is meant by cheque forgery and fraud?",
                                                "answer": "Cheque forgery and fraud refer to illegal acts involving the deceptive alteration, manipulation, or unauthorized creation of a cheque instrument to unlawfully withdraw money from an account.Forgery typically involves replicating the drawer's official signature without permission or altering critical details like the payee's name and payment amount on a valid cheque leaf. Fraud covers broader deceptive practices, such as knowingly issuing a cheque from an inactive account or intentionally passing a cheque with the knowledge that the account lacks sufficient clearing funds, both of which violate negotiable instruments law."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "Explain the reason behind the bank's inability to pay the amount of the cheque given to Mr. Sijan in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "The bank refused to pay the amount of the cheque presented by Mr. Sijan because the financial instrument had legally transformed into a \"Stale Cheque\" (বাসি চেক).Under standard banking regulations and negotiable instrument laws in Bangladesh, a cheque holds a strict statutory validity lifespan of exactly 6 months (180 days) from the date written on its face by the drawer. If a cheque is presented to a banking institution after this six-month clearing window has passed, the bank is legally obligated to reject it to maintain account security and prevent outdated debits.According to the stem, Mr. Rayhan issued and dated the cheque on January 5, 2024 (05-01-2024). Therefore, the legal window during which the bank was authorized to clear and honor this instrument officially closed on July 5, 2024. Since Mr. Sijan went abroad for medical treatment and delayed presenting the cheque until August 1, 2024 (01-08-2024)—which is nearly seven months after its issuance—the instrument had already expired, justifying the bank's direct refusal to disburse the funds."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Is it possible for Mr. Sijan to collect his dues? Give reasons in support of your answer.",
                                                "answer": "1. Confirmation of Legal Recovery Options:\n\nYes, it is entirely possible for Mr. Sijan to collect his dues from Mr. Rayhan. Although the specific paper instrument has expired and the bank has rightfully refused to cash it due to time limitations, the underlying commercial debt and Mr. Rayhan's monetary liability for the transaction remain fully valid under corporate law.2. Revalidation via Counter-Signature:\n\nThe most efficient mechanism for Mr. Sijan to recover his money is to approach the original drawer, Mr. Rayhan, and present the stale cheque to him. Mr. Rayhan can legally revalidate the existing document by crossing out the old expired date, writing a fresh current date above it, and placing his full official signature right next to the alteration to authorize the change.3. Issuance of a Fresh Financial Instrument:\n\nAlternatively, Mr. Sijan can request Mr. Rayhan to officially cancel the stale cheque leaf and issue a brand-new crossed or order cheque for the same amount of BDT 500,000. If Mr. Rayhan acts in good faith, this completely resolves the liquidity issue, allowing Mr. Sijan to deposit the new instrument and collect his funds smoothly through standard clearing channels.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, while the current physical cheque is legally dead at the bank counter, Mr. Sijan's legal right to his money is not lost. By communicating with Mr. Rayhan to either update the date on the old leaf or obtain a completely fresh cheque, Mr. Sijan can easily overcome his administrative delay and successfully recover his business dues."
                                        }
                                ]
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-039",
                                "stem": "Mr. Kamrul handed an BDT 80,000 cheque to his son Rihan and sent him to the bank to withdraw cash. The cheque read, 'Pay to Rihan or bearer eighty thousand taka on demand.' On the way to the bank, the cheque was snatched from Rihan. Rihan immediately informed his father Mr. Kamrul about the incident. In this situation, he is wondering what to do.",
                                "stemImage": "",
                                "meta": "College · 2025",
                                "type": "college",
                                "questions": [
                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is a blank endorsement?",
                                                "answer": "A blank endorsement (ফাঁকা বা অচিহ্নিত অনুমোদন) occurs when the endorser merely signs their name on the back of an order instrument without specifying the name of a particular endorsee, thereby converting the order instrument into a bearer instrument."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Explain the parties to a cheque.",
                                                "answer": "A cheque typically involves three primary legal parties under the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881:1. Drawer (চেকদাতা): The account holder who creates and signs the cheque, issuing an unconditional command to the bank to pay a specific amount of money.\n\n2. Drawee (আদিষ্ট): The specific bank where the drawer holds an active account and which is directed to disburse the funds (e.g., the paying bank).\n\n3. Payee (প্রাপক): The individual or organization designated on the cheque face to receive the specified sum of money. In some cases, the drawer themselves can act as the payee by writing \"Self\"."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of cheque did Mr. Kamrul issue to his son Rihan in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The cheque issued by Mr. Kamrul to his son Rihan in the stem is a \"Bearer Cheque\" (বাহক চেক).According to the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, a bearer cheque is an open financial instrument that can be cashed instantly over the bank's counter by anyone who physically holds and presents the document. It is structurally recognized by the presence of the default phrase \"or bearer\" (অথবা বাহককে) written alongside the payee's name and the complete absence of any restrictive crossing lines across its face.In the given stem, the cheque explicitly states, 'রিহানকে অথবা বাহককে চাওয়ামাত্র ৮০ হাজার টাকা দিন' (Pay to Rihan or bearer eighty thousand taka on demand). Because this phrasing explicitly permits any physical presenter to liquidate the instrument, and there are no protective crossings, it structurally satisfies all criteria of a bearer cheque."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "What do you think Mr. Kamrul should do in the scenario described in the stem? Give your opinion.",
                                                "answer": "1. Immediacy of Financial Risk:\n\nIn the described scenario, Mr. Kamrul faces an immediate risk of financial loss. Because the snatched instrument is an uncrossed bearer cheque, any unauthorized person, finder, or criminal can simply walk into the paying bank branch, present the paper leaf at the teller counter, and withdraw the BDT 80,000 in cash without undergoing rigorous identity verification.2. Primary Action: Issuing a \"Stop Payment\" Order:\n\nThe absolute first and most critical step Mr. Kamrul must take is to immediately contact his bank branch (via phone, internet banking, or physical presentment) and issue an official \"Stop Payment Order\" (চেকের অর্থ পরিশোধ বন্ধের নির্দেশ). He must provide the specific cheque leaf number, account details, and the amount of BDT 80,000. Upon receiving this binding directive from the account holder, the bank will instantly freeze that cheque leaf in their automated system, legally barring the teller from honoring it if presented by the criminal.3. Secondary Protective Actions: GD Filing and Written Notification:\n\nOnce the immediate payment freeze is successfully executed, Mr. Kamrul should file a General Diary (GD) at the local police station regarding the snatching incident to establish a legal shield against potential fraud or misuse of his signature. Following this, he should submit a formal written copy of both the stop-payment request and the police GD to the bank branch manager to permanently document the incident in the institutional records.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, since time is of the essence when dealing with stolen bearer instruments, Mr. Kamrul must act proactively without any administrative delay. By prioritizing an immediate stop-payment order at the bank, he can successfully neutralize the security loophole of the bearer cheque, safeguard his account liquidity, and prevent the stolen funds from being illegally cashed out."
                                        }
                                ]
