                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch6-cq-040",
                                "stem": "Miss Nowrin is an interior designer. She received two cheques as remuneration for her work. On the first cheque, the words \"Miss Nowrin or order\" were mentioned in the payee's name space, and on the second cheque, two parallel lines were drawn diagonally on the top-left corner. She presented both cheques to the bank. Although the bank paid cash against the first cheque, it expressed its inability to give cash against the second cheque.",
                                "stemImage": "",
                                "meta": "College · 2024",
                                "type": "college",
                                "questions": [
                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is an open cheque?",
                                                "answer": "An open cheque is a financial instrument that does not feature any crossing lines drawn across its face and can be presented directly at the counter of the paying bank to obtain immediate physical cash."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "What is meant by the restrictive endorsement of a cheque? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "A restrictive endorsement (সীমিত বা সীমাবদ্ধ অনুমোদন) refers to an act of signing on the back of an order cheque where the holder restricts or completely blocks any further transfer of its ownership to someone else.By using specific phrases like \"Pay to X only\" (শুধু এক্সকে প্রদান করুন), the endorser eliminates the negotiable character of the instrument. This legally binds the bank to disburse the funds strictly to the named individual and prevents further circulating endorsements."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of cheque is the first cheque received by Miss Nowrin in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The first cheque received by Miss Nowrin as remuneration in the stem is an \"Order Cheque\" (হুকুম চেক).According to the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, an order cheque is a financial instrument that is made explicitly payable to a designated person or to their specific order. Structurally, it is identified by the presence of the words \"or order\" (অথবা আদেশানুসারে) written next to the payee's name or by crossing out the default printed word \"bearer\" on the cheque leaf.In the given stem, the first cheque explicitly contained the phrase 'মিস নওরিন অথবা আদেশ অনুসারে' (Miss Nowrin or order). Because it was an open order cheque, it could be legally cashed over the bank counter after proper verification of the payee's identity. When Miss Nowrin presented it, the bank immediately disbursed the cash to her, which conclusively confirms its status as an order cheque."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Evaluate the logic behind the bank's refusal to pay cash to Miss Nowrin against the second cheque in light of the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Structural Shift to a Crossed Instrument:\n\nThe bank's refusal to disburse physical cash to Miss Nowrin against the second cheque is entirely logical, lawful, and aligned with standard monetary regulations. The second cheque features two parallel lines drawn diagonally on its left corner, which structurally transforms it into a \"General Crossed Cheque\" (সাধারণ দাগকাটা চেক).2. Statutory Prohibition of Counter Cashment:\n\nAccording to Section 123 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, the primary legal implication of a crossing is that the paying bank is strictly prohibited from paying physical cash directly over the teller counter. The lines serve as a mandatory directive ensuring that the funds must be routed exclusively through an institutional banking clearing channel. Therefore, the bank teller had no legal authority to hand cash to Miss Nowrin at the counter.3. Institutional Security and Fraud Prevention:\n\nThe bank's refusal is highly justified because it protects the integrity of the financial transaction. Enforcing an account-based deposit creates a permanent digital audit trail within the banking system. If a crossed cheque could be cashed over the counter, the entire mechanism of financial safety, identity verification, and fraud deterrence built into negotiable instruments would collapse.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the bank’s refusal to pay cash over the counter was not a dishonor of the cheque, but a standard regulatory compliance step. To access the funds safely, Miss Nowrin simply needs to deposit the crossed cheque into her own bank account via a standard deposit slip, allowing the clearing house system to safely credit the money."
                                        }
                                ]
                        }
