                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "In light of which principle did Mr. Rifat receive the insurance claim from the insurance institution? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "Data: Mr. Rifat received \"full compensation\" (25 lakh) for his car. <br> Analysis: The core principle of general insurance is to compensate the insured for the actual financial loss incurred, which is known as the 'Principle of Indemnity'. <br> Conclusion: He received the claim under the 'Principle of Indemnity'."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Is it logical for the insurance company to pay the money obtained from selling the damaged car to Mr. Rifat? Give your opinion in light of the stem.",
                                                "answer": "Data: Rifat was fully compensated, but he still wants the 4 lakh BDT from the scrap sale. <br> Analysis: Under the 'Principle of Subrogation', once a full claim is settled, the ownership of the damaged property (wreckage) shifts to the insurer. <br> Evaluation: Rifat has already been restored to his financial position; keeping the scrap money would mean a profit. <br> Decision: No, it is not logical to pay Rifat the sale proceeds. According to the Principle of Subrogation, that money legally belongs to the insurance company."
                                        }
                                ]
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch10-cq-151",
                                "stem": "Mr. 'P' lives in a three-story house registered in his father's name. Considering future accidents, Mr. 'P' went to an insurance company to insure the house, but they refused to insure it. Consequently, Mr. 'P's father insured the house himself. Later, Mr. 'P' started working on a fourth floor without informing the insurance company. This caused the house to lean to the left. When Mr. 'P's father filed an insurance claim, the company refused to fulfill it.",
