                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "Due to which principle did the insurance company not agree to Mr. 'P's proposal in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "Data: Mr. 'P' tried to insure a house registered in his \"father's name.\" <br> Analysis: A person can only insure something if they have a legal financial stake in it, meaning they benefit from its safety and suffer from its loss. This is known as 'Insurable Interest'. Since P doesn't own the house, he has no insurable interest. <br> Conclusion: The proposal was rejected due to the 'Principle of Insurable Interest'."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Analyze the logic of the insurance company's refusal to fulfill the insurance claim for Mr. 'P's father.",
                                                "answer": "Data: The father started construction on a \"fourth floor\" without \"informing the company,\" which increased the risk. <br> Analysis: Under the 'Principle of Utmost Good Faith', the insured must disclose any material changes to the property. Structural changes significantly alter the risk profile. <br> Evaluation: By hiding the construction, the contract was breached. <br> Decision: The refusal is logical. The insurer is not liable for damages caused by an undeclared increase in risk that violates the terms of transparency."
                                        }
                                ]
                        },
