                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Is Mr. Mamun eligible to receive the insurance claim? Analyze in light of insurance principles.",
                                                "answer": "Data: Mamun lied about his age (stated 40 instead of 45). <br> Analysis: Age is a \"material fact\" in life insurance as it determines the risk and premium rate. Providing false information violates the 'Principle of Utmost Good Faith'. <br> Evaluation: While life policies often have an \"incontestability clause\" after 2 years, fraud regarding age usually leads to an adjustment of the claim or cancellation. <br> Decision: He may not be eligible for the *full* claim. The company can either cancel the contract due to misrepresentation or, more commonly, deduct the difference in premiums he should have paid for age 45 from the final payout."
