                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-043",
                                "category": "Knowledge",
                                "question": "What is an insurance premium?",
                                "answer": "An insurance premium is the specific, periodic or lump-sum consideration paid by the insured to the insurance company in exchange for undertaking the financial risk and guaranteeing compensation against potential future losses."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-043-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "What is meant by reinsurance?",
                                "answer": "Reinsurance is a mechanism where an insurance company (the primary insurer) transfers a portion of its corporate risk exposure from an existing policy to another insurance company (the reinsurer) to safeguard its financial stability against massive claims.When an insurance company accepts a high-value or exceptionally risky project that exceeds its financial capacity, it passes a share of that risk—along with a proportional share of the collected premium—to another company, thereby minimizing the danger of total insolvency from a single catastrophic event."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-044",
                                "category": "Knowledge",
                                "question": "What is the principle of subrogation?",
                                "answer": "The principle of subrogation (স্থলাভিষিক্তকরণ নীতি) means that after the insurer fully compensates the insured for a loss, all legal rights, claims, and remedies that the insured had against the liable third party regarding the damaged property are automatically transferred to the insurance company."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-044-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "Why is life insurance not a contract of indemnity?",
                                "answer": "Life insurance is not a contract of indemnity because human life is invaluable, and its loss cannot be measured, quantified, or financially compensated in monetary terms. Under a standard contract of indemnity (such as fire or marine insurance), the insurer promises to restore the insured exactly to their previous financial position before the loss occurred, paying only the actual amount of damage up to the sum assured.Conversely, in a life insurance contract, the insurer agrees to pay a fixed, predetermined sum assured either upon the policyholder's death or upon the maturity of the policy. Since no amount of money can truly replace or calculate the exact loss of a human life, it operates as an investment and security contract rather than a contract of indemnity."
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-045",
                                "category": "Knowledge",
                                "question": "What is moral hazard?",
                                "answer": "Moral hazard (নৈতিক ঝুঁকি) refers to the risk that the insured party may intentionally cause damage, act dishonestly, or behave recklessly to inflate or fabricate a claim, driven by the knowledge that their financial loss is covered by an insurance company."
                        },
