                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-058-b",
                                "category": "Comprehension",
                                "question": "\"Trust is the core element of an insurance contract\"—Explain.",
                                "answer": "\"Trust is the core element of an insurance contract\" because insurance agreements are legally based on the Principle of Utmost Good Faith (চূড়ান্ত সদ্বিশ্বাসের নীতি). Unlike ordinary commercial trades where buyers inspect physical goods, an insurance company cannot completely verify an applicant's internal health or precise risk details through simple observation alone.Both the insurer and the insured must rely entirely on each other's honesty and complete disclosure of material facts. The policyholder must truthfully state their age, health conditions, habits, and occupational hazards, while the company must clearly state its terms and coverage. If either party acts dishonestly, conceals vital facts, or breaks this mutual trust, the insurance contract loses its validity and becomes voidable under law."
