                                                "answer": "1. Identification of the Policy Type:\n\nThe factory owner's decision to issue a single policy for all employees is highly logical, timely, and justified. Legally and structurally, this type of contract is known as a \"Group Insurance Policy\" (গোষ্ঠী বিমাপত্র), which allows an employer to cover a large corporate body of individuals under one master contract.2. Mitigation of Labor Unrest and Rebuilding Trust:\n\nThe primary justification for this managerial step is the resolution of severe human resource vulnerabilities. Following a devastating fire at a nearby facility in Savar, the workers were gripped by extreme anxiety, causing widespread labor unrest. By proactively securing a group life and accident cover, the owner sent a powerful signal that the management values employee safety, effectively mitigating panic, boosting workforce morale, and restoring industrial harmony.3. Administrative and Cost Efficiency:\n\nFrom a financial standpoint, taking out a group insurance policy is vastly superior to issuing separate individual policies for every single laborer. Group underwriting skips rigorous individual medical checkups, simplifies documentation, and dramatically minimizes premium expenses. As highlighted in the stem, this collective approach immediately unlocked a 10% corporate bonus, allowing the enterprise to establish maximum social security for its workforce at a highly optimized operational cost.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the garment manager's decision to adopt a single umbrella policy for all workers is a masterful blend of financial strategy and empathetic crisis management. It successfully safeguarded the business from operational shutdowns caused by labor strikes, minimized corporate premium expenditures, and erected a reliable financial safety net for vulnerable factory workers against workplace hazards like fire accidents."
                                        }
                                ]
                        },
                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-044",
                                "stem": "Mr. Johir took out a 200-year insurance policy with Agroti Life Insurance Company. After his death, he specified his daughter's name as the heir (nominee). Following his death, his son followed the proper procedure to collect the insurance claim and submitted it to the insurance company, but the manager refused to pay the claim, stating that only the daughter would receive the insurance money.",
                                "stemImage": "",
                                "meta": "Rajshahi · 2025",
                                "type": "board",
                                "questions": [
                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is the principle of subrogation?",
                                                "answer": "The principle of subrogation (স্থলাভিষিক্তকরণ নীতি) means that after the insurer fully compensates the insured for a loss, all legal rights, claims, and remedies that the insured had against the liable third party regarding the damaged property are automatically transferred to the insurance company."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Why is life insurance not a contract of indemnity?",
                                                "answer": "Life insurance is not a contract of indemnity because human life is invaluable, and its loss cannot be measured, quantified, or financially compensated in monetary terms. Under a standard contract of indemnity (such as fire or marine insurance), the insurer promises to restore the insured exactly to their previous financial position before the loss occurred, paying only the actual amount of damage up to the sum assured.Conversely, in a life insurance contract, the insurer agrees to pay a fixed, predetermined sum assured either upon the policyholder's death or upon the maturity of the policy. Since no amount of money can truly replace or calculate the exact loss of a human life, it operates as an investment and security contract rather than a contract of indemnity."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What is the reason behind rejecting the claim of Mr. Johir's son in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The bank or insurance manager rejected the claim of Mr. Johir's son because he is not the \"Nominee\" (মনোনীত ব্যক্তি) specified in the official insurance policy contract.According to the Insurance Act, a nominee is a person officially designated by the policyholder during their lifetime to receive the insurance proceeds or claims in the event of the insured's death. Legally, the insurance company is contractually bound to disburse the funds strictly to the individual named on the policy documents, and other legal heirs or family members cannot bypass this designation through standard inheritance claims alone.In the given stem, Mr. Johir explicitly named his daughter as his legal successor and nominee in the insurance policy contract. Even though his son followed the correct physical procedure to submit the paperwork, he does not hold any legal authority within that insurance contract. Because the son's name is completely absent from the nominee field, the insurance manager acted strictly in accordance with legal regulations by rejecting his claim."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "\"Only the daughter will receive the insurance money\"—Analyze the logic behind such a claim by the manager in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Evaluation of the Manager's Decision:\n\nThe claim made by the manager that \"only the daughter will receive the insurance money\" is entirely logical, lawful, and fully justified under current insurance governance and statutory frameworks.2. Legal Rights of the Officially Designated Nominee:\n\nThe core justification lies in the explicit legal status of a nominee in a life insurance contract. When Mr. Johir executed the policy with Agroti Life Insurance Company, he intentionally registered his daughter's name as the sole beneficiary to receive the financial payout after his death. Upon the death of the policyholder, the insurance company's sole legal and fiduciary obligation is to discharge its liability by handing over the sum assured directly to that specified individual.3. Exclusion of Other Family Members from Immediate Payouts:\n\nThe manager's stance is legally robust because insurance companies cannot independently settle family inheritance disputes or divide funds among multiple heirs (like the son) if they are not listed on the policy leaf. If the manager recklessly distributed funds to the son, the company would be held legally liable for breach of contract and wrongful payment. The daughter holds the primary legal certificate of entitlement under the insurance policy's terms.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the insurance company manager acted with complete professional and legal accuracy. While the son may have legitimate inheritance rights under personal or religious laws, those must be settled privately with his sister after the funds are disbursed. From the insurance company's operational standpoint, the contract recognizes only the daughter, rendering the manager's refusal to pay anyone else fully valid."
                                        }
                                ]
