                                                "answer": "1. Core Distinction in Policy Status:\n\nThe insurance benefits realized by Shahin and Tuhin differ fundamentally due to their respective premium compliance. While Tuhin's policy achieves natural maturity as an active contract, Shahin's policy undergoes early termination due to default, shifting its operational framework to a non-forfeiture benefit.2. Tuhin's Financial Yield (Maturity Value):\n\nTuhin successfully maintained his premium payments until the end of the 10-year term. As a result, he is legally entitled to receive the maximum possible financial return from the contract. This includes the full sum assured of BDT 1,200,000 plus 100% of the accumulated bonuses distributed by the company over the decade, providing him with substantial liquid wealth and investment growth during his lifetime.3. Shahin's Financial Yield (Surrender Value):\n\nConversely, Shahin lost his job before maturity and was unable to pay further premiums, causing his active risk coverage to stop. However, his previous investments are protected against total loss by life insurance laws. Since he paid premiums for a significant period before defaulting, his policy has accumulated cash value. He can apply to Delta Life Insurance to receive the \"Surrender Value\" (সমর্পণ মূল্য), which is a mathematically calculated percentage of his total paid premiums, though it will be significantly less than the original BDT 1,200,000 face value and lacks future growth.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, a comparative evaluation highlights that while both friends successfully avoid a total loss of their capital, Tuhin's regular premium consistency rewards him with full maturity values and substantial compound bonuses. On the other hand, Shahin’s unfortunate job loss forces him to settle for a reduced surrender value liquidation, illustrating how financial continuity directly dictates the ultimate payout of an endowment contract."
