                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Why is life insurance called a contract of certainty? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "Life insurance is called a contract of certainty (নিশ্চয়তার চুক্তি) because the occurrence of the insured event—which is either the absolute death of the individual or the expiration of a fixed calendar term—is guaranteed to happen.Unlike indemnity-based general insurance (like fire or marine insurance), where compensation is conditional and paid only if an accident occurs, a life insurance provider is legally bound to pay out the sum assured at some point. Since human death is inevitable and time-bound terms expire naturally, the payout under an active policy is certain, making it a contract of absolute financial certainty."
