                                                "answer": "1. Evaluation of Mr. Solil's Claim:\n\nNo, Mr. Solil's claim to receive a full refund of his entire paid premiums (প্রদত্ত প্রিমিয়াম ফেরত) is not logical, legally valid, or enforceable under insurance statutory regulations. While he is contractually entitled to recover some money, his expectation of a 100% premium reversal is flawed.2. Activation of Surrender Value:\n\nThe legal concept governing this situation is \"Surrender Value\" (সমর্পণ মূল্য). Under life insurance guidelines, if a policyholder stops paying premiums after a minimum required period (typically 2 to 3 consecutive years), the policy does not result in total forfeiture. Since Mr. Solil ran his policy actively from 2020 to 2024 (4 full years) before falling ill and requesting cancellation, his contract had successfully accumulated a tangible cash value within the company's financial reserves.3. Justification for Insurer's Deductions:\n\nAn insurance company cannot fully refund raw premium installments because it actively carried the financial risk of Mr. Solil's life for 4 consecutive years. If he had passed away during that window, the company would have been obligated to pay the full sum assured to his children. During this time, the insurer also incurred operational overheads, medical underwriting costs, and administrative expenses. Therefore, the surrender value is mathematically calculated as a specific percentage of the total premiums paid, minus these risk coverage and management costs.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, while Mr. Solil's decision to close the policy due to health and financial changes is understandable, his demand for a complete premium refund is illogical. He is legally entitled to receive only the accumulated surrender value of the policy, which allows him to retrieve a significant portion of his capital while terminating his lifelong insurance contract safely."
