                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Analyze the logic behind the insurance company's rejection of Mr. Alam's son's insurance claim in the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Evaluation of the Claim Rejection:\n\nThe insurance company's decision to reject the claim submitted by Mr. Alam's son is completely logical, legally justified, and strictly aligned with standard insurance statutory regulations.2. Legal Prerogative of the Registered Nominee:\n\nThe core legal justification relies on the formal status of a \"Nominee\" (মনোনীত ব্যক্তি) within a life insurance contract. A nominee is an individual explicitly designated by the policyholder during their lifetime to receive the financial proceeds of the policy in the event of their death. Contractually and under the Insurance Act, the insurer owes a strict fiduciary duty to disburse the sum assured solely to the individual registered on the policy documents. In this case, Mr. Alam officially registered his wife as the sole successor.3. Exclusion of Other Legal Heirs from Direct Payouts:\n\nEven though the son is a biological child and a legitimate legal heir under personal or religious inheritance frameworks, he does not possess any contractual standing within this specific commercial agreement. Insurance companies are not legal courts; they cannot independently divide claim money among various family members or settle private inheritance distributions if those individuals are not listed on the policy leaf. Disbursing funds to the son would constitute a clear breach of contract, exposing the company to severe legal liability.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the insurance company manager acted with flawless professional and legal accuracy by paying the entire sum assured directly to the wife and turning down the son's separate petition. If the son is entitled to a portion of his late father's wealth under inheritance laws, he must coordinate that matter privately with his mother after she holds the liquidated funds, as the commercial contract recognizes only the registered nominee."
