                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Why is life insurance called a contract of certainty?",
                                                "answer": "Life insurance is called a contract of certainty (নিশ্চয়তার চুক্তি) because the occurrence of the insured event—which is either the absolute death of the policyholder or the expiration of a fixed calendar term—is guaranteed to happen at some point.Unlike indemnity-based general insurance (like fire or marine insurance), where compensation is conditional and paid only if a repairable asset suffers damage, a life insurance provider is legally bound to pay out the sum assured. Since human mortality is inevitable and time-bound terms naturally mature, the financial payout under an active contract is certain, making it a contract of absolute certainty."
