                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "Explain what type of insurance policy Mr. Raju took out.",
                                                "answer": "The insurance policy taken out by Mr. Raju in the stem is an \"Endowment Life Insurance Policy\" (মেয়াদি জীবন বিমাপত্র).According to insurance laws and guidelines, an endowment policy is a temporary or long-term life insurance contract where the insurer guarantees to pay the specified face value or sum assured either upon the natural expiration of a fixed term of years or upon the untimely demise of the insured person, whichever event occurs first.In the given stem, Mr. Raju executed a life insurance contract explicitly bound by a fixed validity timeframe of 18 years and a face value of BDT 600,000. Because this contract blends individual risk protection with a defined calendar maturity period (18 years) requiring periodic semi-annual premium installments, it perfectly reflects the operational and structural characteristics of an endowment life insurance policy."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Evaluate the justification of the money paid to Mr. Raju by the insurance company.",
                                                "answer": "1. Evaluation of the Company's Action:\n\nThe decision of the insurance company to reject Mr. Raju's full maturity claim and instead return a portion of his deposited money is completely justified, logical, and strictly aligned with life insurance statutory legal frameworks.2. Rejection of the Full Maturity Claim:\n\nUnder an endowment contract, the full sum assured (BDT 600,000) is only paid out under two circumstances: if the insured passes away during the term (paid to the nominee) or if the contract successfully reaches its full maturity duration of 18 years. In this case, Mr. Raju did not pass away, nor did he complete the 18-year term. Because he stopped paying premiums after 8 years due to early retirement from teaching, his active policy lapsed, meaning he is legally not entitled to the full sum assured.3. Legal Mechanism of Surrender Value:\n\nThe money returned to Mr. Raju as a \"portion of his deposited money\" represents the \"Surrender Value\" (সমর্পণ মূল্য) of the policy. According to insurance statutory rules, if a policyholder pays premiums for a minimum required period (typically 2 to 3 consecutive years) and then defaults, the previous investments are not forfeited. Since Mr. Raju paid premiums for 8 full years, his contract had accumulated a tangible cash reserve. The company cannot refund 100% of his premiums because it actively bore the risk of his life and managed administrative costs for 8 years. Therefore, returning a mathematically calculated percentage as a surrender value is the correct legal settlement.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the insurance company acted with flawless professional and legal accuracy. While Mr. Raju’s physical disability is highly unfortunate, the insurance company followed proper protocols by denying the premature full claim and safely liquidating the policy's accrued surrender value, providing him with vital liquid capital during his sudden financial hardship."
