                        {
                                "id": "fin2-ch11-cq-062",
                                "stem": "Mr. Arman Mondal, for the financial security of his car valued at BDT 2,000,000, first entered into an insurance contract of BDT 2,000,000 with Shapla Insurance Company. Later, he entered into another insurance contract of BDT 2,000,000 for the same car with Palash Insurance Company. Six months after executing the second contract, Mr. Arman Mondal's car was completely damaged. Mr. Arman Mondal claimed compensation from both companies. Shapla Company paid BDT 1,000,000 and Palash Company paid BDT 1,000,000 as compensation.",
                                "stemImage": "",
                                "meta": "Comilla · 2023",
                                "type": "board",
                                "questions": [
                                        {
                                                "label": "a",
                                                "text": "What is an insurable interest?",
                                                "answer": "Insurable interest (বিমাযোগ্য স্বার্থ) refers to the legal right or financial interest that a policyholder has in the subject matter of insurance, where they stand to benefit from its safety or preservation and suffer a direct financial loss from its damage or destruction."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Must an insurance contract be in writing? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "While an insurance contract does not strictly have to be written to be initially formed under basic contract law, it must practically and legally be in writing to be valid, enforceable, and recognized under standard insurance regulations.An insurance agreement is a conditional and formal contract involving complex clauses, premium calculations, and terms of coverage. A written document, known as the insurance policy (বিমাপত্র), serves as the ultimate legal proof of the agreement between the insurer and the insured. Without a written document, it is virtually impossible to settle claims or resolve legal disputes in a court of law, making written documentation an indispensable requirement."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "c",
                                                "text": "What type of insurance contract did Mr. Arman Mondal execute in the stem? Explain.",
                                                "answer": "The insurance arrangement executed by Mr. Arman Mondal in the stem is an example of \"Double Insurance\" (দ্বৈত বিমা) within a general asset framework.According to insurance laws and principles, double insurance occurs when the exact same subject matter, risk, and financial interest is insured against the same peril with two or more different insurance companies under separate policies during the overlapping time parameters.In the given stem, Mr. Arman Mondal insured his single car—valued at BDT 2,000,000—first with Shapla Insurance Company for BDT 2,000,000, and subsequently with Palash Insurance Company for an additional BDT 2,000,000. Because he opened two independent contracts covering the identical asset and the identical risk profile, his actions structurally fulfill the legal and operational definition of double insurance."
                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "d",
                                                "text": "Did Mr. Arman Mondal receive the correct amount of compensation? Evaluate in light of the stem.",
                                                "answer": "1. Evaluation of the Compensation Amount:\n\nYes, Mr. Arman Mondal received the exact and correct amount of compensation. The settlement of BDT 1,000,000 from Shapla Company and BDT 1,000,000 from Palash Company is perfectly logical, mathematically accurate, and fully aligned with insurance legal frameworks.2. The Core Principle of Indemnity:\n\nCar insurance is a general asset contract governed strictly by the Principle of Indemnity (ক্ষতিপূরণের নীতি). This fundamental rule dictates that insurance is meant to restore the insured to the exact financial position they occupied right before the loss occurred; it is never a tool to generate a commercial profit. Therefore, the maximum compensation a policyholder can legally claim after an accident is capped by the actual financial loss suffered or the face value of the property, whichever is lower.3. Application of the Principle of Contribution:\n\nIn cases of double insurance involving indemnity policies, the Principle of Contribution (অংশদানের নীতি) automatically triggers. When Mr. Arman's car was completely damaged, his actual real-world loss was exactly BDT 2,000,000 (the value of the car). He cannot claim BDT 2,000,000 from both companies separately to pocket BDT 4,000,000, as that would violate the indemnity clause. Instead, the two insurance providers are legally required to split the actual loss proportionally based on their liability ratios:\n$$\\text{Contribution from an Insurer} = \\frac{\\text{Sum Insured with that Insurer}}{\\text{Total Sum Insured across all Policies}} \\times \\text{Actual Loss}$$\n\nSince both companies held equal policies of BDT 2,000,000, they split the loss exactly 50/50, resulting in BDT 1,000,000 from each firm.4. Conclusion:\n\nIn conclusion, the joint settlement perfectly recovered Mr. Arman Mondal’s total asset loss of BDT 2,000,000 without allowing for illegal dual enrichment. The insurance companies acted with absolute legal precision, making the compensation process thoroughly fair and justified."
                                        }
                                ]
