                                        },
                                        {
                                                "label": "b",
                                                "text": "Life insurance is a contract of assurance, not a contract of indemnity' - Explain.",
                                                "answer": "First Paragraph (Cognitive):\n\nLife insurance is considered a contract of assurance rather than indemnity because human life is invaluable, and its financial loss cannot be accurately measured or compensated to restore the exact previous financial state.\n\n\nSecond Paragraph (Analytical):\n\nIn a standard contract of indemnity (like fire or marine insurance), the insurer promises to pay only the actual amount of financial loss suffered up to the policy limit. However, since a human life cannot be valued in monetary terms, the insurer promises to pay a certain, predetermined sum of money either upon the death of the insured or the expiration of a fixed term. Therefore, it assures a fixed financial benefit rather than compensating for a measurable loss, making it a contract of assurance."
