                                                "answer": "First Paragraph (Knowledge/Opinion):\n\nNo, from a strictly operational and logical perspective, there is no absolute requirement or active utility for a nominee in the specific life insurance policy adopted by Mr. Kabir, as long as he survives the maturity period.\n\n\nSecond Paragraph (Understanding):\n\nA nominee is a person designated by the policyholder to receive the policy benefits in the event of the policyholder's untimely death. In pure endowment or fixed-term policies where the benefit is structurally payable only upon survival to maturity, the policyholder themselves receives the money directly, making the nominee's role redundant under normal execution.\n\n\nThird Paragraph (Application & Points):\n\nMr. Kabir's policy has specific attributes that influence this requirement:\n\n* Maturity-Centric Payout: The contract clearly states that Mr. Kabir will receive the insurance claim only upon the expiration of the 15-year maturity period. This means survival is a prerequisite for the payout.\n\n* Primary Claimant Status: Since the payout happens while Mr. Kabir is alive at the end of year 15, he is the primary and sole legal claimant. The funds will be disbursed directly to his account.\n\n* Redundancy of Nominee: A nominee only steps in when the primary insured is deceased. Since death during the term does not trigger a claim under this specific clause, a nominee has no legal grounds to claim money during or at the end of the term.\n\n\nFourth Paragraph (Conclusion):\n\nTherefore, based on the specific condition that the claim is strictly payable only upon the successful completion of the 15-year term, Mr. Kabir will collect the money himself. Hence, a nominee is not necessary for the fulfillment of this specific survival-benefit contract, although companies may keep one on file as a general protocol for legal safety in case of death exactly at the point of maturity."
