                                                "answer": "First Paragraph (Knowledge/Opinion):\n\nYes, 'Gamma' insurance company is legally justified and bound to pay the remaining 5,00,000 TK of the loss to Mr. Nayan, in accordance with the Principle of Contribution (অংশদানের নীতি) in general insurance.\n\n\nSecond Paragraph (Understanding):\n\nThe Principle of Contribution applies strictly to contracts of indemnity (like property or property damage insurance). It dictates that if a policyholder insures the exact same asset with multiple insurers (Double Insurance), they cannot claim the full amount of loss from each company to make a profit; instead, the insurers share the actual loss proportionally, ensuring the insured is only restored to his exact pre-loss financial position.\n\n\nThird Paragraph (Application & Points):\n\nMr. Nayan's scenario illustrates how this proportional sharing mechanism operates:\n\n* Double Insurance Setup: Mr. Nayan took separate, equal policies of 30,00,000 TK each from 'Beta' and 'Gamma' for his factory, establishing a 50:50 risk-sharing ratio between the two insurers.\n\n* Total Measurable Loss: The accident caused a total financial damage of 10,00,000 TK. Since property insurance is a contract of indemnity, Mr. Nayan's maximum total collection across both companies cannot exceed this 10,00,000 TK mark.\n\n* Proportional Liability: Since 'Beta' stepped up and covered its exact 50% legal share by paying 5,00,000 TK, the remaining 50% liability (5,00,000 TK) naturally shifts to 'Gamma' to fully square off the actual damage.\n\n\nFourth Paragraph (Conclusion):\n\nIn conclusion, Mr. Nayan's demand for the remaining 5,00,000 TK from 'Gamma' is completely legitimate. By paying this remaining portion, 'Gamma' fulfills its legal duty under the contribution principle, ensuring that Mr. Nayan recovers his total factory loss of 10,00,000 TK without generating an illegal profit from his double insurance policies."
